Overview & Global Prevalence
Type 2 diabetes mellitus is a chronic metabolic disease characterized by high blood sugar levels resulting from the body's inability to use insulin effectively. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), diabetes affects over 422 million people worldwide, and this number continues to rise at an alarming rate. Unlike Type 1 diabetes, Type 2 diabetes is largely associated with modifiable lifestyle factors such as physical inactivity, poor diet, obesity, and high blood pressure, making it one of the most preventable chronic diseases if identified early.
When analyzing the global spread of Type 2 diabetes by dividing countries into three groups based on geographic location and economic capacity, the data reveals a concerning pattern in the Middle East region. Gulf countries rank highest in diabetes prevalence rates, while Jordan falls within the second tier, reflecting a significant and growing public health challenge. According to the International Diabetes Federation (IDF), the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region has one of the highest diabetes prevalence rates in the world, and Jordan is among the most affected countries in its category, with prevalence rates continuing to rise due to rapid lifestyle changes, increased urbanization, and shifting dietary habits.

This reality, combined with a genuine belief in the importance of early awareness and accessible risk assessment, was the driving motivation behind choosing Type 2 diabetes as the subject of this graduation project. The goal was not only to apply machine learning techniques to a real-world problem, but to contribute — in a meaningful way — to a cause that directly affects the health of individuals and communities in Jordan and the broader region.

Symptoms
One of the most dangerous characteristics of Type 2 diabetes is that it often develops silently. Many individuals live with the condition for years without noticing any obvious symptoms, which is why it is frequently referred to as a silent killer. When symptoms do appear, they tend to develop gradually and may include increased thirst and frequent urination, persistent fatigue, blurred vision, slow-healing wounds or frequent infections, tingling or numbness in the hands and feet, and unexplained weight changes. Because these symptoms can be mild or easily attributed to other causes, a large proportion of individuals remain undiagnosed until the disease has already progressed to a more serious stage.

 Complications
If left unmanaged, Type 2 diabetes can lead to a wide range of serious and life-threatening complications affecting multiple organ systems. Cardiovascular disease is among the most common, as persistently high blood sugar damages blood vessels and increases the risk of heart attack and stroke. Diabetic nephropathy, or kidney damage, is a leading cause of chronic kidney disease and can progress to kidney failure requiring dialysis. Diabetic neuropathy causes nerve damage, particularly in the lower extremities, leading to pain, numbness, and in severe cases, amputation. Vision complications including diabetic retinopathy can result in partial or complete blindness. Additionally, individuals with diabetes are at higher risk of developing depression, cognitive decline, and complications during surgery or illness recovery. These complications represent a real and serious threat not only to individual health and quality of life, but also to healthcare systems and national economies.
 
Treatment & Management

Type 2 diabetes cannot currently be cured, but it can be effectively managed through a combination of lifestyle modifications and medical intervention. The cornerstone of management includes adopting a balanced diet low in refined sugars and saturated fats, engaging in regular physical activity, maintaining a healthy body weight, and monitoring blood sugar levels consistently. When lifestyle changes alone are insufficient, oral medications such as metformin are typically prescribed, and in more advanced cases, insulin therapy may be required. Regular medical follow-up is essential to detect and manage complications early. Importantly, research has shown that in its early stages, Type 2 diabetes can be delayed or even reversed through sustained lifestyle changes, reinforcing the critical importance of early detection and awareness.
